# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batter-cooking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Pasta, meat, and vegetables are central to the cuisine of Abruzzo.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Chili peppers (Italian: *peperoncini*) are typical of Abruzzo, where they are called *diavoletti* (lit.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Due to the long history of shepherding in Abruzzo, lamb dishes are common.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Mushrooms (usually wild mushrooms), rosemary, and garlic are also extensively used in Abruzzese cuisine.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Best-known is the extra virgin olive oil produced in the local farms on the hills of the region, marked by the quality level DOP and considered one of the best in the country.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Renowned wines such as Montepulciano DOCG and Trebbiano d'Abruzzo DOC are considered amongst the world's finest wines.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] In 2012, a bottle of Trebbiano d'Abruzzo Colline Teramane ranked No.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] *Centerbe* is a strong (72% alcohol), spicy herbal liqueur drunk by the locals.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Another liqueur is *genziana*, a soft distillate of gentian roots.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] The best-known dish from Abruzzo is *arrosticini*, little pieces of castrated lamb on a wooden stick and cooked on coals.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] 'guitar') is a variety of egg pasta, with a square cross section about 2–3 mm thick.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] In the province of Teramo, famous local dishes include the *virtù* soup (made with legumes, vegetables, and pork meat), the *timballo* (pasta sheets filled with meat, vegetables or rice), and the *mazzarelle* (lamb intestines filled with garlic, marjoram, lettuce, and various spices).
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] The popularity of saffron, grown in the province of L'Aquila, has waned in recent years.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Seafood also plays an important role in the cuisine of Abruzzo, especially areas near the coast.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Spreadable sausage flavored with nutmeg and liver sausage with garlic and spices are hallmarks of Teramo cuisine.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] *Ventricina* from the Vasto area is made with large pieces of fat and lean pork, pressed and seasoned with powdered sweet peppers and fennel and encased in dried pig stomach.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Atri and Rivisondoli are known for their cheeses.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Mozzarella (fresh or seasoned) is typically made from ewe's milk; many lesser-known cheeses are found throughout Abruzzo and Molise.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] The use of oil in regional mountain and sea dishes is important; among the most common oil products we find the Aprutino Pescarese, the Pretuziano delle Colline Teramane, l'Olio extra vergine di oliva delle Valli Aquilane and Colline Teatine.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] Renowned wines like Montepulciano DOCG, Terre Tollesi DOCG, Trebbiano d'Abruzzo DOC and Controguerra DOC are judged to be amongst the world's finest.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] In 2012, a bottle of Trebbiano d'Abruzzo ranked No.
[src:batter-cooking/abruzzese-cuisine] IGT wines are Alto Tirino, Colli Aprutini, Colli del Sangro, Colline Frentane, Colline Pescaresi, Colline Teatine, Del Vastese (or Histonium), Terre di Chieti, and Valle Peligna.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine is not very well known in Canada or internationally.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] It has much in common with Québécois cuisine because of its geographical proximity.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] The two often feature the same dishes, but the cuisine of Acadia puts more emphasis on seafood.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine has notably served as the base for Cajun cuisine because the Cajun are descendants of Acadians who were deported to Louisiana.Note 2 It is also believed that Acadians are responsible for normalizing potato consumption in France—a vegetable the French once considered poisonous.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] In the 17th century, French colonists who settled on lands they named Acadia adapted their 16th-century French cuisine to incorporate the crops, seafood and animals that flourished in the region.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Their descendants became the Acadian people and their ingenuity created Acadian cuisine.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] After the English conquered Acadia during the 18th century, they decided to deport the Acadians and take their settlements, which were often built on the most fertile earth in the colony.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Most Acadians did not manage to escape the deportation.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] But, of those who did, most fled to the east and north of New BrunswickNote 3.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] As such, Acadian cuisine in the 18th century was refocused around what could be grown, hunted and fished in the less fertile lands of the East Coast of New Brunswick and the Upper St.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine often features fish and seafood, especially cod and Atlantic herring, but also mackerel, berlicoco, lobster, crab, salmon, mussels, trout, clams, flounder, smelt and scallops.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Most fish is consumed fresh, but some are *boucané* (smoked), marinated or salted.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] The most commonly used meat is pork, followed by chicken and beef.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] As with the rest of North America, turkey is commonly consumed during the holidays.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Game like deer, hare, ruffed grouse and moose is consumed regularly in some regions.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Game will replace livestock meat if present and can be given as a gift.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] In some regions, for example Caraquet and the Îles-de-la-Madeleine, more unusual game is or was caught, like seal, bear and seagull.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] The vegetables of Acadian cuisine are the potato, onion, carrot, turnip, legume, beet, squash and corn.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] These vegetables were popular because they were easily preserved for the winter in root cellars and jars.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] The fiddlehead fern was introduced to the Acadians by the indigenous Maliseet, Mi'kmaq and Penobscot peoples in the early 18th Century and remains a popular Acadian dish.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Popular fruits include blueberries, apples, strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, plums, pears and cranberries.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Some ingredients like rice, molasses, dried raisins and brown sugar are part of Acadian cuisine because of historical commerce between Acadia and regions like the Antilles and Brazil.
[src:batter-cooking/acadian-cuisine] Maple sugar is also a popular sweetener, given the often-close familial ties between Quebec (the world's largest producer of maple sugar) and Acadia.
[src:batter-cooking/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:batter-cooking/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] Porous ceramic diffusers are made by fusing aluminum oxide grains using porcelain bonds to form a strong, uniformly porous and homogeneous structure.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] The naturally hydrophilic material is easily wetted resulting in the production of fine, uniform bubbles.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] On a given volume of air or liquid, the surface area changes proportionally with drop or bubble size, the very surface area where exchange can occur.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] Utilizing extremely small bubbles or drops increases the rate of gas transfer (aeration) due to the higher contact surface area.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] The pores which these bubbles pass through are generally micrometre-size.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] Aeration in food is a process by which air is absorbed into the food item.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] Such processes produce lightness in cakes and bread by creating larger and more numerous pores.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] Chemicals and foodstuffs added to enhance this effect can be known as leavening agents.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] The color and texture of some sauces, pastes, and confections are also affected by air bubbles.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] One of the most frequent instances of such aeration in cooking is the whipping of egg white to produce foam.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] Egg whites and other substances added to enhance similar aeration—such as the soy protein or gelatine added to American nougat in candy bars—are known as whipping agents or aerating agents.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] In wine tasting, a variety of methods are used to aerate the wine and bring out the aromas, including swirling wine in the glass, using a decanter to increase exposure to air, or using a specialized wine aerator.
[src:batter-cooking/aerate] Cider from Asturias is poured into the glass from a height of about 1 metre (*el escanciado*) to increase aeration.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] The cuisine of Afghanistan is *halal* and uses various herbs and spices including coriander, mint, dill, cumin, cardamom and turmeric as well as locally-grown saffron.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Afghan dishes are typically mild in flavor.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] A variety of rice dishes known locally as 'palao' are prepared with various fruits, nuts and legumes, and combine sweet and sour flavors central to Afghan cuisine.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Dumpling and noodle dishes, meat and vegetable stews, legumes, and kebab dishes make up the bulk of Afghan cuisine.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Rice is a core staple food in Afghan cuisine and the most important part of any meal.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Challow, or white rice cooked with mild spices, is served mainly with *qormas* (*korma*: stews or casseroles).
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Palaw is cooked similarly to challow, but a combination of meat, stock, *qorma*, and herbs are also mixed in before baking, resulting in the elaborate colors, flavors, and aromas from which the rice got its name.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Sometimes caramelized sugar is used to give the rice a rich brown color.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Afghan bread is flat and cooked in a tanoor or tandoor (a vertical ground clay oven).
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] The bread is slapped onto a stone wall to cook.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Tabakhai is a flatbread cooked on a flat upside-down pan.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Known under the name *khameerbob* and often eaten as dumplings, they are rarely served at large gatherings, such as weddings.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] They are instead served on special occasions at home.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Qormah (also spelled "korma" or "qorma") is an onion- and tomato-based stew or casserole usually served with challow rice.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] First, onion is caramelized, for a richly colored stew.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Then tomato is added, along with a variety of fruits, spices, and vegetables, depending on the recipe.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] The main ingredient, which can be meat or other vegetables, is added last.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Afghan kabob is most often found in restaurants and at outdoor street vendor stalls.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Most of the time, it contains lamb meat.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Kabob is made with naan instead of rice.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Customers have the option to sprinkle sumac or *ghore angoor* (dried ground sour grapes) on their kabob.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Pieces of fat from the sheep's tail (*jijeq*) are usually added to the skewers to add extra flavor.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Traditional Afghan kabobs are made with onion juice, lemon, yoghurt, black pepper and sometimes saffron for chicken.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Other popular kabobs include the lamb chop, ribs, *kofta* (ground beef), and chicken.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Chapli kebab, a specialty of eastern Afghanistan, is a patty of minced beef.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] It is a popular barbecue meal in Afghanistan.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] It is prepared flat and round and served with naan.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] The original recipe of chapli kabob dictates a half-meat, half-flour mixture which renders it lighter in taste and less expensive.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] This type of kabob contains herbs and sometimes chilli.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Afghan chicken or *murgh-e* is a classic example of one of the most famous dishes of Afghanistan.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Chicken dishes are usually found in restaurants and at outdoor street vendor stalls.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Unlike in the Indian cooking style, chicken in Afghan cuisine is often used with the intention that it be *halal*.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Cream, butter, and curd are customary ingredients in all chicken recipes, whether served as an appetizer or a main course.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] As a dessert after a meal, most Afghans generally eat fresh fruit.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] For snacks, they may drink tea with something sweet like cakes, cookies or pastries.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] On occasions, they also eat dried fruits which are widely available in every Afghan market.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Chai is tea in Afghanistan, which can either be green or black.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] It is consumed at all times, especially a short time after finishing a meal or with guests during any social gathering.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Most people drink green tea with no sugar.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Doogh (also known by some Afghans as *shomleh* or *shlombeh*) is a cold drink made by mixing water with yogurt and then adding fresh or dried mint.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Some variations of doogh include the addition of crushed or diced cucumber chunks.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] It is the second most widely consumed drink in Afghanistan (the first being tea), especially during lunchtime in summer.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Doogh can be found at almost every Afghan grocery store and is served in restaurants.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] While Afghans have a common cuisine, certain ethnicities form sub-variations of it.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group of Afghanistan, constituting about 42% of the country's total population.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] A major dish in Pashtun culture are rosh (cooked lamb and mutton with no spices) and sohbat, found at traditional gatherings and events.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Other major Pashtun dishes include lamb-skewered *sajji* and *chapli kebab*.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] The name *dampukht* stands for steamed meat, and *khaddi kebab* is the Afghan shashlik, which is grilled on an open fire, on a spit.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Although it differs between regions, Pashtun cuisine is meat-heavy and often includes caramelized rice.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] For example, the dish known as *bolani* in the north and east is often called *borogyen* in the south and west of Afghanistan.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Common summer beverages include *shlombeh*, a drink consisting of liquid yogurt, mint, and cucumber.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] *Sher yakh* is a sweet ice-like product.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] The Hazara people in central Afghanistan (in the region of Hazarajat) and western Pakistan (Balochistan province) have their own fare.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] The Hazaragi cuisine shares some similarities with neighboring regional cuisines, so it is mainly influenced by Central Asian, Persian, and South Asian cooking.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] However, cooking methods vary in some of the dishes of these neighboring cuisines.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Traditionally, dinners are served on a tablecloth on the floor, which is called the *dastarkhan*.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Meals are normally eaten with the right hand.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] After a meal, tea with dessert is served.
[src:batter-cooking/afghan-cuisine] Serving tea and white sugared almonds (called *nuql*) is customary during Afghan festivals.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Each region in Africa has developed its own distinctive culinary practices, shaped by local ingredients, colonial history and trade.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In **West Africa,** for example, dishes often feature rice, millet, and beans complemented by spicy stews made with fish, meat, and leafy greens.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The use of chili peppers, peanuts and palm oil is also widespread in this region.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] **Central African** cuisine on the other hand, tends to be simpler and relies heavily on starchy foods such as cassava and plantains, often served with sauces made with peanuts or vegetables.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In **East Africa**, particularly in countries like Kenya, Tanzania, and Uganda, the cuisine reflects a combination of native agricultural practices and influences from trade routes with India and the Middle East.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Staples such as maize, beans, and rice are commonly consumed along with dishes like Ugali (a maize-based porridge) and sukuma wiki (a dish made from collard greens).
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The coastal areas of East Africa, particularly along the Swahili coast, feature seafood and curries seasoned with spices such as cardamom and cloves, a direct influence of Indian and Arab traders.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] **Southern African** cuisine also displays a blend of indigenous ingredients and colonial influences.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Dishes such as pap (a maize-based porridge) and biltong (a type of sausage) are popular in countries like South Africa, Botswana, and Namibia.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The cuisine is characterized by the use of game meat, maize, and beans, as well as European influences introduced during colonial times.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Traditionally, the various **cuisines of Africa** use a combination of plant-and seed-based ingredients, without having food imported.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In some parts of the continent, the traditional diet features an abundance of root tuber products.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Africa represents a rich history of adaptation, trade, and resourcefulness. while regional differences are pronounced, the use of local ingredients and traditional cooking techniques remains central to the continent's culinary identity.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Central Africa, East Africa, North Africa, Southern Africa and West Africa each have distinctive dishes, preparation techniques, and consumption modes.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The roots of native African cuisine goes back to thousands of years before the Bronze Age in Northeast Africa, when early civilizations began cultivating grains such as barley and wheat.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Part of North Africa is in the Fertile Crescent where settled agriculture was practiced by the Ancient Egyptians in this area.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Animals such as donkeys and sheep were also domesticated, starting the spread of agriculture to other parts of Africa, notably West Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Although most tribes still lived a simple hunter-gather diet.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Arab explorers- Leo Africanus and Ibn Battuta- provided accounts of African food which they encountered on their travels through sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Most European travelers stayed close to coastal areas until the 19th century.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Many of their diaries also recorded details on foods and crops.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Many staples were introduced later when Africa was colonized by the Europeans.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Foods that are now important parts of African cuisine such as maize and potatoes were not common until the 19th century.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The influence of African food on Caribbean, Brazilian, American Lowcountry cuisine, and Cajun cuisine from Louisiana is seen in rice dishes and green stews like the Afro-Caribbean efo, duckanoo and callaloo.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The vegetable okra, introduced from Africa, is used in classic Louisiana gumbos, and American rice growing in the Carolina.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Lowcountry was influenced by West African techniques of rice cultivation and many slaves hailed from the rice-growing regions of West Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Lowcountry cuisine is still known for its distinctive rice dishes.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Central Africa expands from the Tibesti Mountains in the north to the vast rainforest basin of the Congo River, the highlands of Kivu and the savannah of Katanga.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] This region has received the culinary influence of the Swahilis (culture that evolved via the combination of Bantu, Yemeni, Omani and Indian cultures) during the trans-Saharan slave trade.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Swahili culinary influences can be found in dishes such as mandazi, pilaf rice, kachumbari, sambusa, and kuku paka.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Central African cuisine has also been influenced by the Portuguese, by way of the Kongo and Ndongo Kingdoms.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Salt fish was introduced following trade in the late 17th century, and the Kikongo term for salt fish, makayabu, comes from the Portuguese term bacalhau.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Portuguese culinary influence is especially prominent in Angola, Sao Tomé and Equatorial Guinea.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Central Africa has also been influenced by the cuisine of the East, West and Southern Africa regions because of their close proximity, e.g. babuté or bobotie is shared with the south, nyama choma with the east and sauce gombo with West Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In Central Africa, a variety of crops are grown, including yams, cassava, bananas and plantains, sweet potatoes, and cocoyams.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] These crops have become staples in the diet of many people in Central Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Fufu-like starchy foods are usually made from fermented cassava roots, but they can also be made with plantain, corn maize and yam.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Fufu is served buffet-style with grilled meat, fish, stews, greens and piment .
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A variety of local ingredients are used while preparing other dishes, like spinach stew cooked with tomato, peppers, chilies, onions, and peanut butter.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Eastern central Africa is also one of the few regions in Africa that uses potatoes as one of its main bases, since potatoes grow easily in the region.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Cassava plants are also consumed as cooked greens.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Groundnut (peanut) stew is also prepared, containing chicken, okra, ginger, and other spices.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Beef and chicken are favorite meat dishes, but game meat preparations containing crocodile, elephant, antelope and warthog meats are also served occasionally.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The cuisine of East Africa varies from area to area.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In the inland savannah, the traditional cuisine of cattle-keeping peoples is distinctive meaning that meat products are generally absent.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Cattle, sheep, pigs and goats were regarded as a form of currency and a store of wealth.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] They are not generally consumed as food.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In some areas, traditional East Africans consume the milk and blood of cattle, but rarely the meat.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Elsewhere, other Africans are farmers who grow a variety of grains and vegetables.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Maize (corn) is the basis of ugali', the local version of West and Central Africa's fufu.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Ugali is a starch dish eaten with meats or stews.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In Uganda, steamed green bananas called matoke provide the starch filler of many meals.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Around 1000 years ago, Omani and Yemeni merchants settled on the Swahili Coast.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Middle Eastern influences are especially reflected in the Swahili cuisine of the coast—steamed or cooked rice with spices in Persian style; saffron, cloves, cinnamon and several other spices; and pomegranate juice.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Several centuries later, the British and the Indians came, and both brought with them foods such as Indian spiced vegetable curries, lentil soups, chapattis and a variety of pickles which have influenced various local dishes.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Some common ingredients used in this region include oranges, lemons, limes, chilies, capsicum peppers, maize, tomatoes, and strawberries.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In the Horn of Africa, the main traditional dishes in Eritrean cuisine and Ethiopian cuisine are tsebhis (stews) served with injera (flatbread made from teff, wheat, or sorghum) and hilbet (paste made from legumes, mainly lentils and fava beans).
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian cuisine (especially in the northern half) are very similar, given the shared history of the two countries.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian food habits vary regionally.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In the highlands, injera is the staple diet and is eaten daily among the Tigrinya.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Injera is made out of teff, wheat, barley, sorghum or corn, and resembles a spongy, slightly sour pancake.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] When eating, diners generally share food from a large tray placed in the center of a low dining table.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Many injera are layered on this tray and topped with various spicy stews.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Diners then break into the section of injera in front of them, tearing off pieces and dipping them into the stews.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In the lowlands, the main dish is akelet, a porridge-like dish made from wheat flour dough.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A ladle is used to scoop out the top, which is filled with berbere and butter sauce and surrounded by milk or yoghurt.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A small piece of dough is broken and then used to scoop up the sauce.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The best known Ethiopian/Eritrean cuisine consists of various vegetable or meat side dishes and entrées, usually a wat, or thick stew, served atop injera, a large sourdough flatbread made of teff flour.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] One does not eat with utensils, but instead uses injera to scoop up the entrées and side dishes.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Tihlo, prepared from roasted barley flour, is very popular in Amhara, Agame, and Awlaelo (Tigray).
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Traditional Ethiopian cuisine employs no pork or shellfish of any kind, as they are forbidden in the Jewish and Ethiopian Orthodox Christian faiths.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] It is also very common to eat from the same dish in the center of the table with a group of people.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Somali cuisine varies from region to region and consists of an exotic mixture of diverse culinary influences.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] It is the product of Somalia's rich tradition of trade and commerce.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Despite the variety, there remains one thing that unites the various regional cuisines: all food is served halal.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] There are therefore no pork dishes, alcohol is not served, nothing that died on its own is eaten, and no blood is incorporated.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Varieties of bariis (rice), the most popular being basmati, usually serve as the main dish.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Spices like cumin, cardamom, cloves, cinnamon and sage are used to aromatize these different rice dishes.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] During Ramadan, dinner is often served after Tarawih prayers, sometimes as late as 11 pm.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Xalwo (halwo) or halva is a popular confection served during special occasions such as Eid celebrations or wedding receptions.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] It is made from sugar, cornstarch, cardamom powder, nutmeg powder, and ghee.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Peanuts are also sometimes added to enhance texture and flavor.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] After meals, homes are traditionally perfumed using frankincense (lubaan) or incense (cuunsi), which is prepared inside an incense burner referred to as a dabqaad.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Food and nutrition security in East Africa (Rwanda, Burundi and South Sudan) is a significant issue.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The region has been plagued by drought, conflict and economic instability since the 1990s.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The current situation is characterized by low levels of food availability and high levels of malnutrition among young children.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The solution proposed for this problem is to increase local food production.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] This would be achieved by increasing agricultural productivity by improving soil fertility and water management, which will help farmers grow more crops per year.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] This will also help reduce poverty in the region by providing more employment opportunities for local people.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In a study of food loss and waste in North Africa, researchers found that the region was wasting about 30% of its food, which is likely to increase as the population continues to grow.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] This waste occurs for a variety of reasons, including lack of refrigeration and storage facilities.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] To solve this issue, the people had to get creative with new dishes and ways of storing food.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The more we looked, the more we found that people were using all parts of plants in some way—the leaves, stems, flowers, fruits and seeds.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] They also used every edible part of animals as well—from fat to bones for making broth or soup.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] North Africa lies along the Mediterranean Sea and encompasses within its fold several nations, including Morocco, Algeria, Libya, Tunisia, and Egypt.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The roots of North African cuisine can be traced back to the ancient empires of North Africa, particularly in Egypt, where many of the country's dishes and culinary traditions date back to African antiquity.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Over several centuries traders, travelers, invaders, migrants and immigrants all have influenced the cuisine of North Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Phoenicians of the 1st century brought sausages, while the Carthaginians introduced wheat and its by-product, semolina.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Berbers adapted semolina into couscous, one of the main staple foods.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Olives and olive oil were introduced before the arrival of the Romans.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] From the 7th century onwards, the Arabs introduced a variety of spices, like saffron, nutmeg, cinnamon, ginger and cloves, which contributed and influenced the culinary culture of North Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Ottoman Turks brought sweet pastries and other bakery products, and from the New World, North Africa got potatoes, tomatoes, zucchini and chili peppers.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In addition, two completely different dishes may also share the same name (for example, a tajine dish is a slow-cooked stew in Morocco, whereas the Tunisian tajine is a baked omelette/quiche-like dish).
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] There are noticeable differences between the cooking styles of different nations, from the sophisticated, full-bodied flavors of Moroccan palace cookery to the fiery dishes of Tunisian cuisine and the humbler, simpler cuisines of Egypt and Algeria.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The cooking of the Southern Africa region (not to be confused with the country of South Africa) is sometimes called "rainbow cuisine", as the food in this region is a blend of many cultures: indigenous African societies, European, and Asian.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] To understand indigenous African cuisine, it is important to understand the various native peoples of southern Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The indigenous Africans of Southern Africa were roughly divided into two groups and several subgroups.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The largest group consisted of the Bantu-speakers, whose descendants today may identify themselves by various subgroup names such as Ndebele (northern and southern), Shona, Venda, Zulu, Xhosa, Swazi, Sotho, Tswana, Pedi and Tsonga.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] They arrived in the region around 2,000 years ago, bringing crop cultivation, animal husbandry, and iron toolmaking with them.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Hence the Bantu-speakers grew grain crops extensively and raised cattle, sheep and goats.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] They also grew and continue to grow pumpkins, beans, and leafy greens as vegetables.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A smaller group were the primeval residents of the region, the Khoisan, who some archaeologists believe had lived in the region for at least 10,000 years.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Many descendants of the Khoisan people have now been incorporated into the population of South Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Khoisan originally were hunter-gatherers (who came to be known as "San" by the Bantu-speakers and as "bushmen" by Europeans).
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] After the arrival of the Bantu-speakers, however, some Khoisan adopted the Bantu-speakers' raising of cattle but did not grow crops.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] People were, in other words, defined to some extent by the kinds of food they ate.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Bantu-speakers ate dishes of grain, meat, milk and vegetables, as well as fermented grain and fermented milk products.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] While the Khoi-Khoi ate meat and milk and the San hunted wild animals and gathered wild tubers and vegetables.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In many ways, the daily food of native South African families can be traced to the indigenous foods that their native African ancestors ate.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Khoisan and Bantu traditionally ate roasted meat, and they also dried meat for later use.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The influence of their diet is reflected in the universal Southern African love of barbecue (generally called in South Africa by its Afrikaans name, a "braai") and biltong (dried preserved meat).
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The traditional beer was ubiquitous in the southern African diet, and the fermentation added additional nutrients to the diet.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] It was a traditional obligation for any family to be able to offer a visitor copious amounts of beer.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Beer brewing was done by women, and the status of a housewife in pre-colonial southern Africa depended significantly on her skill at brewing delicious beer.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Milk was historically one of the most important components of the southern African diet.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Cattle were considered a man's most important possession.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In order to marry, a man had to compensate his prospective in-laws with a gift of cattle as a dowry for his bride.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A married man was expected to provide a generous supply of milk to his wife and children, along with meat whenever he slaughtered cattle, sheep or goats.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Because there was no refrigeration, milk was mostly soured into a kind of yogurt.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The young men of the family often took care of the cattle far away from the villages at "cattle posts," and they sent a steady stream of yogurt home on behalf of their fathers.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Today, many South Africans of African origin enjoy drinking sour milk products that are sold in the supermarket, comparable to American buttermilk, yogurt, and sour cream.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] On weekends they will have a "braai", and the meal usually consists of "pap and vleis", which is maize porridge and grilled meat as has historically been done in the region.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The basic ingredients include seafood, meat products (including wild game), poultry, as well as grains, fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Fruits include apples, grapes, mangoes, bananas, papayas, avocado, oranges, peaches and apricots.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Desserts may simply be fruit, but there are some more western-style puddings, such as malva pudding, reminiscent of sticky toffee pudding, which was inspired by both British cuisine and Dutch cuisine.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Meat products include lamb, and game like venison, ostrich, and impala.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The seafood includes crayfish, prawns, tuna, mussels, oysters, calamari, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] There are also several types of traditional and modern alcoholic beverages including many European-style beers.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A typical West African meal is made with starchy items and can contain meat, fish, as well as various spices and herbs.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A wide array of staples are eaten across the region, including fufu, banku, kenkey (originating from Ghana), foutou, couscous, tô, and garri, which are served alongside soups and stews.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Fufu is often made from starchy root vegetables such as yams, cocoyams, or cassava, and also from cereal grains like millet, sorghum or plantains.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The staple grain or starch varies between regions and ethnic groups, although corn has gained significant ground as it is cheap, swells to greater volumes and creates a beautiful white final product that is greatly desired.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Banku and kenkey are maize dough staples, and garri is made from dried grated cassavas.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Rice dishes are also widely eaten in the region, especially in the dry Sahel belt inland.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Examples of these include the Senegalese dish thieboudienne also known as benachin or Jollof rice, a pan-West African rice dish similar to Arab kabsah.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Seeds of Guinea pepper (Aframomum melegueta, also called grains of paradise or melegueta pepper), a native West African plant, were used as a spice and even reached Europe, through North African middlemen, during the Middle Ages.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Centuries before the influence of the Europeans, West Africans were trading with the Arab world and spices like cinnamon, cloves, and mint were not unknown, therefore becoming part of the local flavorings.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Centuries later, the Portuguese, French and British influenced the regional cuisines, but only to a limited extent.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques include roasting, baking, boiling, frying, mashing, and spicing.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] A range of sweets and savories are also prepared.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques of West Africa are changing.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In the past West Africans ate much less meat and used native oils (palm oil on the coast and shea butter in Sahelian regions).
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Baobob leaf and numerous local greens were everyday staples during certain times of the year.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Today the diet is much heavier in meats, salt, and fats.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Many dishes combine fish and meat, including dried and fermented fish.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Flaked and dried fish is often fried in oil, and sometimes cooked in sauce made with hot peppers, onions, tomatoes, various spices (such as soumbala), and water to prepare a highly flavored stew.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] In some areas beef and mutton are preferred, and goat meat is the dominant red meat.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Suya, a popular grilled spicy meat kebab flavored with peanuts and other spices, is sold by street vendors as a snack or evening meal and is typically made with beef or chicken.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] It is common to have a preponderance of seafood, which as earlier stated, is sometimes also mixed with other meat products.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Guinea fowl and chicken eggs are also preferred.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] With regard to beverages, water has a very strong ritual significance in many West African nations (particularly in dry areas) and water is often the first thing an African host will offer their guest.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Palm wine is also a common beverage made from the fermented sap of various types of palm trees and is usually sold in sweet (less-fermented, retaining more of the sap's sugar) or sour (fermented longer, making it stronger and less sweet) varieties.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The exact origins of Bitter Leaf soup appear to be unknown thought it is known to have been prepared and eaten for hundreds of years.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The dish traditionally consists of fish, meat (usually beef), bitter leaves, palm oil, and an array of spices and seasonings.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Shellfish such as shrimp or crayfish are often used alongside fish in the preparation of Bitter Leaf Soup.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] Due to the bitterness of bitter leaf, the bitter leaf is washed thoroughly to diminish the bitterness before being cooked with the rest of the ingredients.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] It is widely consumed in West Africa, especially Nigeria where it is associated with the Igbo people and referred to as Ofe Onugbu.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The Bitter Leaf itself is known scientifically as Vernonia amygdalina and is native to Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:batter-cooking/african-cuisine] The bitter taste comes from the alkaloids contained within the plant.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] There are very few Ainu restaurants in the world, though some do exist.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Examples of Ainu restaurants include Haru Koro (Harukor) in Shinjuku, Tokyo, Ashiri Kotan Nakanoshima in Sapporo, and Poron'no and Marukibune in Akan, Hokkaidō.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Traditional Ainu cuisine used meats obtained through fishing and hunting such as salmon and deer, wild plants gathered in the mountains such as *Cardiocrinum cordatum* bulbs (**turep**) and acorns, as well as various grains and potatoes obtained through farming.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Another feature is its liberal use of oils as flavoring.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Due to the Ainu's reliance on local game and fauna, not all areas used all the same ingredients, instead utilizing what was most available.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] In addition to salt, the fats (**sum**) from cod, sardines, herring, shark, seal, whale (**humpesum*),* sika deer (**yuksum**), and bear (**pasum**) are used to flavor dishes.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Miso and soy sauce have also been used in modern times.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Soup stocks may be made using kelp (*kombu*), animal bone, and dried fish.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Seasoning and spices include **pukusa** (*Allium ochotense*), berries from the Amur corktree (*Phellodendron amurense*), and wavy bittercress (*Cardamine flexuosa*).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The most predominate game animal was the sika deer.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Deer were hunted using poisoned arrows as well as by herding them off cliffs and gathering them from where they fell.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] In the past, deer were so common and easily hunted in Hokkaidō that it was said one could “put the pot on the fire, then go hunting”.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu fished at sea in dugout canoes using harpoons to hunt a variety of large marine animals and used nets and fishing rods to bring in smaller creatures.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Beached whales were particularly prized, as generally it was impossible to bring a whale in using canoes and harpoons.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] However, there were some instances of whaling in Funka Bay using harpoons coated with wolfsbane poison, aided by the gentle tides.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu also used a number of tools including fishing rods, nets, traps (**uray**), and fishing baskets (**raomap**) to catch freshwater fish.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] While men were responsible for hunting and fishing, women were responsible for gathering edible plants, beginning in early spring.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Tools used during gathering trips into the mountains included the **saranip** (a bag woven from the fibers of the Japanese lime tree), the **menoko makiri** (a small women's knife), **itani** (a type of digging stick), and the **shitap** (a small pick made from deer horn).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] One of the most important mountain plants gathered in spring was the Siberian onion (**pukusa**), which is very similar to wild leeks found in Canada and the United States in taste, texture, and appearance.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Large quantities of *Cardiocrinum cordatum* bulbs (**turep**) were gathered in summer as they were important as a preserved food.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Farming was already taking place in Hokkaidō during the Jōmon period, prior to the Satsumon period in which the Ainu culture first emerged.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] However, agriculture began to decline in the 12th century up until the Ainu period.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This is thought to be caused by the increase in demand for dried fish and furs for trade with Honshū, leading to increased importance in hunting and fishing, rather than colder weather.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Cultivated crops changed over the years as new crops were introduced, such as potatoes, kabocha, and beans.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The resulting paste is flavored with minced spring onion, **pukusa**, or long-stamen chive.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Finally, the **citatap** is seasoned with dried kelp and salt.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Other than salmon, a variety of meats and fish are used to add flavor to **citatap** such as Japanese dace, *bathyraja lindbergi*, masu salmon, Japanese fluvial sculpin, deer, bear, tanuki, rabbit, and chipmunk.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] **Citatap** was well suited to the meat of older animals, as it made the tough meat easier to eat.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] **Citatap** was primarily made in the winter, when food spoiled more slowly, and was eaten over a number of days.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] If the **citatap** was not particularly fresh, it was formed into balls and added to soup.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Roughly chopped meat or fish is added to the stock and cooked.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Dried meat and fish require longer cooking times.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The scum that results from cooking the meats is not removed, as it was thought to have medicinal properties.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Root vegetables or those which required longer cooking times are added, followed by high fiber mountain vegetables, and finally leafy vegetables.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The soup is allowed to cook further until all ingredients are soft.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The soup is flavored with animal or fish fats, a small amount of salt, and topped with ground dried kelp or dried **pukusa**.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Different varieties of **ohaw** are named by their main ingredient such as **cep ohaw** (fish soup), **kamuy ohaw** (bear soup), **kam ohaw** (meat soup), and **kina ohaw** (vegetable soup).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] *Anemone flaccida* was particularly suited for use in soups and was therefore called **ohaw kina**, which literally translates as “soup grass”.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Translated literally, **rataskep** means “mixed food”.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Wild vegetables and beans are stewed until soft and the liquid has evaporated, at which point the mixture is mashed and seasoned with bear or fish oils and a small amount of salt.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] **Rataskep** was made as an everyday food, as well as for offerings at ceremonies, as it was considered a sacred food.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] There are unlimited varieties using different ingredients, below are a few examples.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] ) is rehydrated in hot water, then boiled over low heat for hours until the water evaporates.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It is cut into easy-to-eat pieces and seasoned with animal fat and salt.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] ) stalks are added and cooked further, then seasoned with animal fat and salt.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Beans are boiled until soft, then angelica is added and further boiled.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Finally, it is seasoned with animal and fish fats.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] ) are rehydrated in water then boiled along with the beans.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] ) is placed in a separate pot and cooked over low heat until it starts to break down.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The skin is removed from the cooked potatoes and they are sliced thickly before placing into the pot with the salmon roe.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Salt is added and everything is mixed well.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] ) which are then boiled and drained multiple times with the seed coat on to remove the bitter taste.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] They are then placed in water with beans and boiled together.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The water is replaced and the mixture is boiled further until soft, at which point corn flour is added.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It is cooked to the desired consistency.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Rice flour is added, the mixture is kneaded, and salt and animal fats are added for seasoning.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] A thin porridge made from boiling Japanese millet or rice.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Generally, the grains are boiled alone, but occasionally gathered vegetables are added.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Unlike other porridges in agricultural societies, **sayo** is not a staple food.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Rather, Ainu would fill up on fatty soups and grilled meats then drink it like tea as a palate cleanser.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] For that reason, **sayo** was made in a small dedicated pot so as to avoid mixing oils in from other dishes.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Care was also taken to avoid mixing flavors when serving by using a separate ladle specifically for serving **sayo** (**sayo kasup**), rather than the usual ladle for serving soup (**kasup**).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] As the porridge used very little grains to make, a month's supply for one person was approximately 1.8 liters.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] 108 liters would provide plenty for a family of five for a year.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The following are examples of *sayo* varieties.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] is first ground with mortar and pestle, then rehydrated in water.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] ) is boiled along with the grain porridge.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Raw salmon roe was only eaten in the fall as a delicacy.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The name **sito** is derived from the Japanese **shitogi** which refers to dumplings or a paste made from grinding raw grains.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Traditionally, **sito** were considered a luxury due to the time and effort necessary to produce the flour by grinding the grains with mortar and pestle.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It was therefore not a usual everyday food, but one made as offerings for sacred days such as the Bear Festival (**iomante**) and Ancestors’ Festival (**icarup**).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Usual ingredients were proso millet (**mankul**), foxtail millet (**munchiro**), and rice (**siamam**), though **sito** made with proso millet were considered the correct form.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Over the years, other ingredients were added such as pumpkin (**kabocha**), and potato (**imo**).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Similar to the Japanese *kusamochi*, the Ainu also made **sito** which mixed in Japanese mugwort (**noya**).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Their flavor was enjoyed as reminiscent of spring.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The grains are placed in a large mortar and multiple people sing while pounding the grain with large pestles (**iutaupopo**).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The resulting flour is kneaded with hot water and formed into round flat dumplings approximately 7 or 8 centimeters in diameter and 1 centimeter thick.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The dumplings are boiled in a large pot, taking care not to allow them to burn on the bottom of the pot.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu word for dried meat is **satkam** while dried fish is called **satcep**, **nikeruy**, or **atat**.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Salmon was fished in quantities greater than what could be eaten immediately, especially in fall, and processed into preserved food so it could last up to six months.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The first step in the process was to remove the head and internal organs of the fish, which was then dried on a rack outside before being taken inside and smoked in the hearth.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Trout (**icaniw**) and Japanese char (**tuksis**) caught in summer were dried over a fire to prevent flies damaging the fish.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] These dried fish were eaten as is by pulling off the meat, or by rehydrating in water and eating as ingredients in soup or as a final cooked item itself.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Salmon that was dried after the fish had laid eggs lost much of its flavor, so it was often stewed with added fish fats to improve the taste.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Milt (**up**) and salmon roe (**cipor**) obtained when slicing open the fish were also dried and preserved then later used in **sayo** or to make stock for **ohaw**.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] While it was common to eat everything of a bear raw while it was still fresh, including its meat and its internal organs, the Ainu would also preserve some of the meat for consumption during the off season.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Meat from deer (**yuk**) and brown bears (**kimun kamuy**) was cut into narrow strips and simmered in a large pot.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Once the juices were removed, the meat was hung over the fire inside to dry and smoke.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This **satkam** would be eaten as is, or boiled again to create a soup.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The starch obtained from *Cardiocrinum cordatum* bulbs (**turep**) held a more important position in the Ainu diet than grains.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu word for the fourth month of the lunar calendar is **mo kiwtacup**, which translates to “soon to be time to dig up **turep** month”, while the fifth month is **si kiwtacup**, or “digging up **turep** month”.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This was the time when Ainu women would take their sacks (**saranip**) and digging sticks (**itani**) and head into the mountains to gather the bulbs.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The gathered bulbs were processed into starch using the following method.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Grind until a sticky paste is formed using the head of a hatchet as a pestle.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Pour large quantities of water into the bucket and let sit for about two days.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Fine fibers and skins will float to the surface of the water forming a scum after a few days have passed and the starch will settle to the bottom.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The fibrous scum is removed and set aside for use in on turep.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The starch collected on the bottom of the bucket is divided into two types of starch: the semi-liquid secondary starch and the powdered primary starch.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] These two types of starch were dried and preserved, but before that, they were also used to make fresh foods.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The primary starch was mixed with water and poured into the hollow of plant stems from the Japanese knotweed (**kuttar**) or *Parasenecio hastatus* (**wakkakutu**) and placed into the ashes of a fire to cook into a thin noodle-like shape.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The secondary starch was formed into round dumplings, wrapped in the leaves of the Japanese butterbur (**korkoni**) or magnolia (**pusni**), then placed in the ashes of a fire to bake.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] They were then eaten with salmon roe or animal fats.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The secondary starch was the one which was used on a daily basis once it had been dried for preservation.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It was often formed into dumplings and added to **sayo**.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The primary starch was rarely eaten, instead being reserved for gifts or used as medicine.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It was considered taboo to speak of alcohol or love affairs while working on any part of the starch making process.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It was said such discussions would agitate the starch and it would fail to settle properly.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The water is thoroughly wrung from the fiber, then it is wrapped in leaves from the Japanese butterbur (**korkoni**) or *Parasenecio hastatus* (**wakkakutu**) and left to ferment for three to ten days.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This fermenting process is called “**on**”.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The fermented product is ground thoroughly with a mortar and pestle.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Once pounded, it is kneaded, formed into donut-like shapes, and dried.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] A cord is passed through the center and the **on turep** is stored hung from a rack above the hearth.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The **on turep** was eaten by smashing and rehydrating it to form into dumplings and placed in **sayo**.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Once potatoes were harvested in the fall, the poorly shaped and small potatoes were left outside.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The winter's cold would soon come and freeze the potatoes, which would thaw again in spring.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This process of freezing and thawing would break down the structure of the potatoes, turning them soft.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Once in that state, the potatoes were soaked in water and thawed completely.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The starch that settled to the bottom of the water was collected, formed into spheres, and arranged in a warm place to ferment.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This resulted in a fine textured potato flour.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The flour was formed into cakes and baked in the ashes of the fire, then bear fat or **cipor** (salmon roe) was added and together placed in **sayo** to eat.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] In modern times with the influence of ethnic Japanese culture, it became more common to flavor **pocche-imo** with artificial flavorings such as saccharin then deep fry them.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The fried product is then eaten with nori or a mixture of sugar and soy sauce.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Words for alcohol in the Ainu language include *sake*, *tonoto*, and *askur*.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The word sake is a loanword from Japanese, and *tonoto* is also a word developed under Japanese influence as it originally referred to food or beverages given by an influential Japanese person, who was called a *ton*.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Ainu alcohol is an undistilled alcohol made from Japanese millet that is similar in appearance and flavor to homebrewed sake.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Virtuous, respected *katkemat* (ladies/wives) from nearby were considered suitable for leading the task.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Conversely, young women, particularly those during *menokotasum* (menstruation, literally translated as “women sickness”) were considered impure and did not assist.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The ingredients considered best for making alcohol were Japanese millet (*piyapa*) or proso millet (*menkul*).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] First, the grains were heated in a large pot with water until a porridge formed.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Once cool to the touch, malt was mixed in.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu either acquired malted grain from trade with the Japanese or they produced their own by boiling Japanese millet, acorns, and *Cardiocrinum cordatum* then sprinkling powdered bark from the *Cercidiphyllum* tree on the finished product.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Furthermore, the Ainu word for malt, *kamtaci*, is the same as the old Japanese word for malted rice, *kamutachi*.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The alcohol was stored in a lacquered vessel (*sintoko*) and left to set in hot embers as a warding against evil.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Using a portion of *Apehuci-kamuy*, the goddess of fire, like this would protect the alcohol from evil spirits, and was a prayer for the success of the alcohol making process.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] As an additional warding against evil spirits, a hatchet (*tasiro*) or an Ainu blade (*emus*) was placed atop the sintoko as it was left to set for ten days near the *kamuy puyar*, the window furthest inside the cise, which was considered sacred.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Once the alcohol had fermented enough, the spent coals were returned to the hearth and the mash was strained through a sieve (*icari*) to remove the lees (*sirari*) and finish the alcohol.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It was stirred using a sake ladle (*sake-pisakku*), ladled into a spouted bowl (*etosup*), then poured into bowls (*itanki*).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] When offering alcohol to the spirits, an *ikupasuy*, a ceremonial stick, was dipped into a bowl of sake set on a *takaysara*, a bowl stand.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The alcohol on the *ikupasuy* was then spread onto the *inau*.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] It was believed that by going through the *ikupasuy*, one drop of alcohol in the human world would become an entire barrel of alcohol in the spirit world.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu said that alcohol was something that everyone enjoyed, along with the spirits.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu of the Hidaka region, such as those near Shizunai, had a legend that tsunami spirits hated lees, so they spread the lees around their homes to ward off tsunamis.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The teas drunk by Ainu were not made with the evergreen *Camellia sinensis*, but from the seeds and bark of trees, or medicinal herbs native to the cool climate of Hokkaidō.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] In the Sakhalin region, drinks were made of boiled *Ledum palustre* (*nuxca*) stems and leaves, *Rose rugosa* (*otaruxni*), and *Rubus matsumuranus* (*kinakaoxni*) stems and leaves.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Japanese tea imported from Honshu has become widespread in modern times.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] There are some trees native to Hokkaidō that contain a sweet sap.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Ainu used the sap of these trees (*niwakka,* literally translated as “tree water”) as a drink and flavoring for foods.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Large amounts of sap run from the trunk of the white birch (*kapattatni*) if it is damaged in the summer.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This sap is called *tatni wakka* and was used as water for cooking when there was none available in the area.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] A drink was also made by adding chopped *Symplocarpus nipponicus* to the sap along with flavoring.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The Sakhalin Ainu would make alcohol by placing set white birch sap into blackcurrant juice and leaving it to ferment.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The painted maple (*topeni*, meaning “milk tree”) is related to the sugar maple of North America.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] A sweet sap flows from the trunk if it is damaged.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The trunks would be scored during the winter to make “sap icicles” that were eaten like popsicles.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The sap was also boiled down to create a sweetener.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This was then boiled with beans or water chestnuts to make a high-quality *rataskep*.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Sap fell out of use along with the influx of sugar during the Meiji Period, but it experienced a temporary resurgence during the shortages of World War II.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Traditionally, two meals were eaten per day, breakfast (**kunneywa ipe**) and dinner (**onuman ipe**), and a third meal, lunch (**tokes ipe**), was added during the Taisho period.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] A night meal (**kunne ipe**) was sometimes eaten during night fishing or other late activities.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Food was transferred from the cooking pot using a ladle (**kasup**) into a lacquerware bowl (**itanki**) for eating.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] These bowls were obtained through trade with the ethnic Japanese and were large enough to hold 400 ml worth of food.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Chunks of meat or fish that were too large to fit in the bowl were placed on mats woven from reeds.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Items such as fish roasted on a spit or **sito** were eaten by hand, but otherwise, most foods were eaten with chopsticks (**pasuy**) or spoons (**parapasuy**).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] **Parapasuy** translated literally means “wide chopstick”.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Both spoons and chopsticks were carved from wood.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] When guests were over for food, the head woman of the house would offer food and say “**ipeyan**” (please eat).
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] The guest would express their gratitude, and, if it were a valuable meal such as bear meat, they would raise the food to their forehead in thanks before beginning.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] However, the family would not say anything before eating if there were no guests.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Once finished, it was customary to say “**hunna**” to express their gratitude for the food.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Similar to the ethnic Japanese, it was considered polite to eat all food that was provided.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] Because of this, it was considered polite to use one's finger to wipe the remaining sauce from inside the bowl and lick it.
[src:batter-cooking/ainu-cuisine] This custom is the reason for the Ainu name for the pointer finger, “**itanki kem atsukep**”, literally meaning “bowl-licking finger”.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] The word *batter* comes from the French word *battre*, which means *to beat*, as many batters require vigorous beating or whisking in their preparation.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Many batters are made by combining flour with liquids such as water, milk, or eggs.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Batters can also be made by soaking grains in water and grinding them wet.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Often a leavening agent such as baking powder is included to aerate and fluff up the batter as it cooks, or the mixture may be naturally fermented for this purpose as well as to add flavour.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Carbonated water or another carbonated liquid such as beer may instead be used to aerate the batter in some recipes, such as for Fanta cake.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Other substitutes for water are wine, or flavored liquors like curaçao, brandy, and maraschino.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] The viscosity of batter may range from very "heavy" (adhering to an upturned spoon) to "thin" (similar to single cream, enough to pour or drop from a spoon and sometimes called "drop batter").
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Heat is applied to the batter, usually by frying, baking, or steaming, to cook the ingredients and to "set" the batter into a solid form.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Batters may be sweet or savoury, often with either sugar or salt added (sometimes both).
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Many other flavourings such as herbs, spices, fruits, or vegetables may be added to the mixture.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Beer is a popular ingredient in batters used to coat foods before frying.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] One reason is that a basic batter can be made from merely flour, beer, and some salt.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] The purpose of using beer is so the bubbles in the beer will add body and lightness to the batter.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Depending on the type and quality of the beer, it may also add colour or some flavour to the batter.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] The practice of beer battering is popular in Australia, New Zealand, the United States, Britain, Ireland, Germany, Iceland and Russia.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Foods that are commonly beer-battered and fried include fish, chips, and onion rings.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Batters are used in many cuisines under many names.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Tempura in Japan, pakoda and dosa in India, *galapong* in the Philippines, spoonbread in the US, and many other examples are all types of batters.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] The ideal batter for fried foods is to be thick enough to adhere to the food, but not so thick as to become heavy.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Batters made with wheat flour thicken with every second that passes after mixing because of the development of gluten.
[src:batter-cooking/batter-cooking] Strategies to reduce this effect include the use of ice water when mixing, alcohol (which does not mix with the flour to produce gluten), and making it at the last possible moment before use.
